- Avoid redirection
Even if we hit http:// the website redirects to https:// like flipkart.
https://hstspreload.org

- Resousrce hinting
![alt text](image-3.png)
preconnect(connect to specific cross origin server in advance)
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://cdn.glitch.global" crossorigin />
![alt text](image-4.png)

dns-prefetch(does DNS lookup in advance)
<link rel="dns-prefetch" href="https://cdn.glitch.global" crossorigin />
![alt text](image-5.png)

preload(Initiate early request to resource for rendering the page)
<link rel="preload"
    href="https://cdn.glitch.global/db01a8e4-9230-4c5c-977d-85d0e0c3e74c/image-1.jpg?v=1669198400523" as="image" />
<link rel="preload" href="/font.woff2" as="font" crossorigin/>
![alt text](image-6.png)

prefetch(load resources which are needed in near future with low-priority - future)
<link rel="prefetch" href="/next-page.css" as="style" />

prerender(loads entire page and all its dependency in background which display hidden)
<link rel="prerender" href="blog.html" />

Read: https://web.dev/learn/performance/resource-hints

- Resource Hint priority
![alt text](image-7.png)
onload="this.rel='stylesheet'"
This helps in downloading the stylesheet as preload, then it'll be convertes it to stylesheet so that it gets parsed.
The high priority gets loaded first, then the low.
<img
    src="https://cdn.glitch.global/db01a8e4-9230-4c5c-977d-85d0e0c3e74c/image-4.jpg?v=1669198402935"
    alt="Image 4"
    class="image"
    fetchPriority="high"
/>
Read: https://web.dev/articles/fetch-priority

- Early hints
![alt text](image-8.png)
Read: https://developer.chrome.com/docs/web-platform/early-hints
Example:
GET /main.html
Host: example.com
User-Agent: [....] Chrome/103.0.0.0 [...]
103 Early Hints
Link: <https://fonts.google.com>; rel=preconnect
Link: </main.css>; rel=preload; as=style
Link: </common.js>; rel=preload; as=script

- HTTP updgrade methods(http1.1 vs http2 vs http3)
![alt text](image-9.png)
![alt text](image-10.png)
Http1 -> it can make 6 paralle requests only, until any one of it completes others will be on hold and uses http://
Http2 -> this works on purely https:// and also needs ssl certificates, this will make multiple parallel requests unline http1
https://github.com/namastedev/namaste-frontend-system-design/blob/master/Performance/Network%20Optimization/example4/index.js
https3 -> used for streaming like youtube and netflix

- Compression: gzip, brotli
This is used to compress the content using library which comes from server.
brotli compression is br, main.bundle.js.br
![alt text](image-12.png)
![alt text](image-11.png)
Read: https://web.dev/articles/codelab-text-compression-brotli

